To retrieve and display information about potential resources for starting a new business, you can create a simple C# console application. Since the information on resources like SCORE, Small Business Administration, Entrepreneurial Networks, Trade Associations, and Online Business Communities is not available via a specific API, you'll need to collect and store this information manually or use web scraping (if allowed by the website's terms of service) to fetch the data.

Below is a basic example of how you might structure a C# application to display this information. This example assumes that you have predefined data about these resources:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Generic;

namespace BusinessResourcesApp
{
    class Program
    {
        static void Main(string[] args)
        {
            List<Resource> resources = GetBusinessResources();
            DisplayResources(resources);
        }

        static List<Resource> GetBusinessResources()
        {
            var resources = new List<Resource>
            {
                new Resource
                {
                    Name = "SCORE",
                    Description = "SCORE is a nonprofit organization that provides free, confidential business mentoring and training workshops to small business owners.",
                    Website = "https://www.score.org/"
                },
                new Resource
                {
                    Name = "Small Business Administration (SBA)",
                    Description = "The SBA is a United States government agency that provides support to entrepreneurs and small businesses.",
                    Website = "https://www.sba.gov/"
                },
                new Resource
                {
                    Name = "Entrepreneurial Networks",
                    Description = "Networks that connect entrepreneurs with peers, mentors, and investors to foster business growth.",
                    Website = "Example: https://www.entrepreneur.com/"
                },
                new Resource
                {
                    Name = "Trade Associations",
                    Description = "Organizations founded and funded by businesses that operate in a specific industry.",
                    Website = "Example: https://www.uschamber.com/"
                },
                new Resource
                {
                    Name = "Online Business Communities",
                    Description = "Online platforms where business owners can connect, share advice, and collaborate.",
                    Website = "Example: https://www.reddit.com/r/smallbusiness/"
                }
            };

            return resources;
        }

        static void DisplayResources(List<Resource> resources)
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Potential Resources for Starting a New Business:\n");

            foreach (var resource in resources)
            {
                Console.WriteLine($"Name: {resource.Name}");
                Console.WriteLine($"Description: {resource.Description}");
                Console.WriteLine($"Website: {resource.Website}");
                Console.WriteLine("\n");
            }
        }
    }

    class Resource
    {
        public string Name { get; set; }
        public string Description { get; set; }
        public string Website { get; set; }
    }
}
```

### Explanation:
- **Data Structure**: A simple `Resource` class is used to store information about each resource, including its name, description, and website.
- **Data Collection**: The `GetBusinessResources` method returns a list of `Resource` objects. You can expand this list with more detailed data as necessary.
- **Display Functionality**: The `DisplayResources` method iterates through the list of resources and prints their details to the console.

This structure allows you to easily add or update information about resources. For dynamic data retrieval, you would typically look into APIs or web scraping techniques, depending on the source of information.
